---
import Container from '../components/Container.astro';
import FadeIn from '../components/FadeIn';
---

<section class="py-20 sm:py-28 bg-bone-white">
  <Container>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center">
      <FadeIn client:visible direction="left">
        <div class="aspect-[4/3] rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-coconut-cream shadow-lg">
          <img
            src="/images/family/founder.jpg"
            alt="D'Timer Cafe founders in the early years"
            class="w-full h-full object-cover"
            loading="lazy"
            onerror="this.src='https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559339352-11d035aa65de?w=800&q=80'"
          />
        </div>
      </FadeIn>

      <div>
        <FadeIn client:visible direction="right">
          <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm font-body font-medium tracking-[0.25em] uppercase text-sambal-red">
            The Beginning
          </p>
        </FadeIn>

        <FadeIn client:visible delay={0.15} direction="right">
          <h2 class="mt-3 font-display text-3xl sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-semibold text-warm-black leading-tight">
            From a family kitchen to a neighbourhood institution.
          </h2>
        </FadeIn>

        <FadeIn client:visible delay={0.3} direction="right">
          <p class="mt-5 text-base sm:text-lg text-tea-brown leading-relaxed">
            D'Timer Cafe opened its doors in 2008 with a simple mission: 
            serve Johor cuisine in KL that actually tastes like home. 
            The recipes came from family — the Laksa Johor broth from a grandmother's 
            kitchen, the Nasi Ambeng from Eid gatherings, the Kacang Pool from 
            weekend breakfasts in Johor Bahru.
          </p>
        </FadeIn>

        <FadeIn client:visible delay={0.45} direction="right">
          <p class="mt-4 text-base sm:text-lg text-tea-brown leading-relaxed">
            Wangsa Maju was chosen because it was a growing neighbourhood 
            full of young families and students — people who missed the 
            flavours of the south but couldn't always make the trip home. 
            Word spread. The lines grew. And seventeen years later, 
            D'Timer is still run by the same family, still using the same recipes.
          </p>
        </FadeIn>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Container>
</section>
